New York Moves — But
Not Equally

When you walk through New York City, you feel possibility everywhere but you also see the gaps.

Physical education time has steadily decreased across many NYC schools, leaving students with fewer opportunities to move, play,

and build lifelong healthy habits. The inequity is most visible in low-income districts where staffing, equipment, and facility access

are limited.

As community leagues shrink and private clubs expand, thousands of kids, especially in underserved neighborhoods, are

priced out of structured sport. Access now depends more on income than interest or talent, leaving many youth without

safe, consistent ways to become and stay active.

New York’s older adults face barriers ranging from unsafe sidewalks to limited strength and balance programming. Many want to

stay active but lack the structured support needed to maintain mobility, independence, and social connection.

Adaptive programs, accessible facilities, and trained staff remain unevenly distributed across the city. Too many New Yorkers with

disabilities encounter physical, logistical, and cultural barriers that prevent full participation in movement, recreation, and sport.

Movement as a Right, Not a Privilege

My mission is to help build a coordinated movement ecosystem where every New Yorker, in every borough, at every age, of every ability has access to safe, meaningful, culturally relevant opportunities to move.

A Citywide Movement
Framework — Beyond the Silos

Sports and recreation are often viewed as “nice to have,” but they are among NYC’s strongest tools for improving public health, mental wellbeing, school outcomes, work force performance and community safety.

NYC’s movement system is fragmented. Agencies, schools, facilities, community groups, and nonprofits all work hard, but they operate separately. The issue isn’t talent or effort. It’s misalignment.

My vision unifies these pieces into a coordinated, citywide movement ecosystem that serves every New Yorker with clarity,

consistency, and access. (Full framework in the NYC Sports, Wellness and Recreation Strategy Deck.)

Three Concise Strategic
Clusters

Ensuring every New Yorker across every borough, age, income level, and ability has real opportunities to move.

Modernizing and activating the parks, facilities, and public spaces that shape our daily lives.

Movement pathways through every stage of life from youth play to adult recreation to aging well.

Why This Moment Matters

Rising inactivity, mental health strain, and widening inequity threaten the wellbeing of millions. At the same time, we’re seeing unprecedented innovation, community energy, and public interest in wellness.

The opportunity is clear. We can connect schools, parks, community centers, public facilities, healthcare, and workplaces into a coordinated movement ecosystem that serves every neighborhood and every New Yorker.
